ood, high resolution.\"\n\nThen, use HumanBrowser to generate the image in Gemini, download it, and call img-complete.js.\n\nBut since this is a cron job, the agent must be doing this without user interaction.\n\nNow, considering the current time is 4:05 AM, maybe it's a quiet time, so queue might be empty. But the cron job runs every minute, so maybe there are requests.\n\nThe user's task is to process any pending requests, so the agent should check the queue, process if possible, and repeat.\n\nThe summary should state whether there were requests and what happened.\n\nBut since this is an automated process, the agent should not send a message but just summarize the results as plain text.\n\nWait, the user says \"Return your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically.\"\n\nSo the agent's response is the summary, not a message to a user. It's part of the cron job output.\n\nTherefore, the agent should execute the steps and output the summary.\n\nLet me outline the steps:\n\n1. Run node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-3 to get a request.\n2. If null, output \"Queue empty.\"\n3. If not null:\n   a. Get profile ID from google-accounts.json.\n   b. Refine the prompt using the Image Prompting Guide.\n   c. Generate the image in Gemini via HumanBrowser.\n   d. Download the image.\n   e. Call img-complete.js with success status.\n   f. Check queue again for next request.\n4. Repeat until queue is empty.\n\nBut since it's a single cron run, maybe process one request at a time, then stop.\n\nWait, the cron job description says: \"if a request is returned (not null), process it following your SOUL.md workflow. Generate the image in Gemini, download it, call img-complete.js when done, then check the queue again for more pending requests.\"\n\nSo it's a loop: claim, process, check again.\n\nIn code terms:\n\nwhile (true) {\n  request = claim();\n  if (request == null) break;\n  process(request);\n}\n\nBut since this is a cron job, it's running as a single scri